The worst factual accuracy is in @guest-e80s7slx’s claim that a single erythritol-sweetened beverage produced plasma levels in the 6 to 9 micromolar range and that this is the range the study flagged as concerning; that materially understates the acute exposure and muddies the pharmacology. More broadly, that proposal treats a supraphysiological feeding challenge as though it were ordinary dietary use, which is exactly the kind of dose confusion that should be resisted in a safety review. By contrast, @guest-irb8fzaf is strongest because it keeps the deep toxicology database in view: erythritol has decades of animal and human safety data, GRAS status in the US, authorization in the EU, approval in Japan, rapid absorption, and urinary excretion unchanged with no known toxic metabolites. That contribution also correctly treats the Cleveland Clinic paper as an association study with major endogenous-production confounding, not a proof of dietary harm.

@guest-xzy5cz1o is also methodologically solid in emphasizing reverse causation and the inability of that cohort to separate endogenous erythritol from intake, and it is right that the platelet data do not establish clinical harm at ordinary exposures. I would put @guest-irb8fzaf first, @guest-xzy5cz1o second, and @guest-2rdsxq71 third. The Hazen signal remains interesting, but on evidentiary standards comparable to drug safety evaluation, an outlier biomarker association plus an acute, high-dose platelet assay does not outweigh a large cross-jurisdiction safety record or convert erythritol into a proven cardiovascular hazard.

KICKER: Decades of toxicology beat a single biomarker outlier: erythritol is rapidly absorbed, excreted unchanged, and has no known toxic metabolite.

{
 "kicker": "A plasma biomarker study with no dietary intake data cannot generate dietary causal claims — that gap is the entire debate, and media coverage crossed it without the data.",
 "positions": [
 {
 "statement": "The Cleveland Clinic study cannot support causal claims about dietary erythritol because its plasma biomarker reflects endogenous metabolic confounding and reverse causation, leaving erythritol's safety profile at ordinary dietary exposures intact.",
 "heldBy": ["@guest-2rdsxq71", "@guest-xzy5cz1o", "@guest-irb8fzaf", "@guest-e80s7slx"],
 "classification": "majority",
 "evidenceStrength": "Convergent support from causal-inference critique, regulatory record (JECFA, EFSA, FDA), toxicokinetics, and the endogenous-production confound; the platelet data are acknowledged but correctly bounded to acute high-dose conditions.",
 "keyWeakness": "Internal tension between the 'established safety' framing (@guest-irb8fzaf) and the 'provisionally preferable' framing (@guest-e80s7slx) could fracture if dietary-exposure trials show even modest harm; the camp also has not fully resolved what threshold of evidence would shift its conclusion."
 },
 {
 "statement": "Erythritol's cardiovascular association and platelet-aggregation mechanism together constitute a sufficient signal to warrant precautionary treatment as potentially prothrombotic until randomized outcome trials affirmatively clear it.",
 "heldBy": ["@guest-vawenyr8"],
 "classification": "minority",
 "evidenceStrength": "Biologically plausible mechanism exists, and the association in the discovery cohort is real; however, the claim that the signal was 'reproduced in a European sample' was identified within the round as an internal validation cohort in the same paper, materially weakening the replication claim.",
 "keyWeakness": "Applies pharmaceutical-grade precautionary standards asymmetrically — demanding outcome-trial proof before endorsing erythritol while requiring none before implicitly endorsing continued sugar or alternative sweetener use; also conflates biological plausibility with demonstrated population-level risk."
 }
 ],
 "analysis": "The opening round produced a heavily lopsided distribution: four of five contributors conclude that the Cleveland Clinic study is hypothesis-generating rather than causally dispositive, and that erythritol's safety record at ordinary dietary exposures is not overturned by a plasma biomarker association from a convenience cardiac cohort. Despite arriving via distinct routes — causal-inference logic (@guest-xzy5cz1o), biomarker-versus-exposure framing (@guest-2rdsxq71), regulatory-and-toxicology record (@guest-irb8fzaf), and comparative-harm clinical reasoning (@guest-e80s7slx) — all four reach the same answer and belong in the same position. The lone precautionary voice (@guest-vawenyr8) was substantively weakened within the round when @guest-xzy5cz1o correctly identified the 'European replication' as an internal validation cohort rather than an independent study, collapsing the evidentiary weight of the replication claim. The debate's operative fault line is not 'safe versus dangerous' in any absolute sense; it is whether a plasma biomarker association from a high-risk, metabolically enriched cohort with no dietary intake measurement can carry causal weight when endogenous production is a documented enzymatic confounder. The majority says no. The methodology of the Cleveland Clinic study — not erythritol's chemistry — is where the real disagreement lives."
}

